Mar 7 2026

This week James Watson noted he wasnt convinced about Granger causality yet. Did I test it out all properly. 
That got me to think about testing it with a toy example, where I generate data where its only on way causal, so rain comes down,
and sinks into soil, but it does not go back up again. Using this datafile I then did a granger causality test on it.
It actually did find a significant fstat at time lag 1 month, when it should not have. This suggested that there is a rain persistence
effect, where the soil water still looks like it is predicting the rain.

I also noticed that I found there depending on how I processed data - detrend or difference it seemed like it might shift when the 
tws >1m water affected the rain. It looked like with detrending it was a 1 month lag, while differencing led to 2 month lag peak.
This 1 month peak is possibly problematical because the one way causal toy data suggested that some 1 month peaks could be spurious.

So this led me to think more about using the tws-smap data, as that for many places had a 2 month lag. 

On looking more at this tws-smap data, where I looked at MJJ (May,June,July) and ASO months differently. It said that for MJJ it had
2 month and 3 month lags. This would suggest that in March and April the tws was already going to impact the MJJ months. So this
suggests that there may be a priming, tws could be bringing in the onset of rain. For the retreating ASO months there was also 2 and 
3 month lag, which suggests that the tws could be extending the wet season. 

When I looked at the soil moisture 5cm it showed that it was having a 1 month lag for impacting MJJ and ASO months. However when I then 
did a shuffle test, where I shuffled the month (say october) with month (october from another year) from another year, then it disappeared.
And also shuffling chunks of 3 months. So it was a spurios effect. However the tws >1m -> rain still was real, it survived the two
types of shuffle tests.

Mar 20
I had to do a paper for my stats final on a paper that used something we learnt in class. So I looked at Findell and Eltahir 1997 paper on how soil moisture 
affects rain in Illinois. They looked at the soil moisture on one day, and saw if it correlated with rain for the next 21 days. And then plotted 
that soil moisture vs rain, and looked to see if it had a pattern. They did linear regression and saw a fit. 

So that got me to thinking I could use linear regression to look at tws on rain. I tried the feb tws to see how it affected the rain the next year from mar to feb 
in places in Sahel. At first I thought I saw a positive correlation. But then I took into account that the tws started trending up in 2018. If I just did
the year up to 2017 I saw rather an negative correlation in many places, as tws went down in feb, the rain for the upcoming year went up. 

I also looked at whether tws one month could predict the next month rain, it seemed it could, and sometimes not just one, but sometimes two and three.

I decided to look at a cell centered in Illinois. I used tws in feb to see if it predict rain next year. It borderline does r=.43, p=.055. The rain from previous year 
also could with r=..14, p=.055 . But problem is here there is a lot of pumping. I also saw that the previous months tws could predict future months of rain. 
In apr and may is when there is less pumping. So Apr tws can affect may and june rain, and not so strongly july. Impact is more than the rain. 

